ce:section.ce:para:
Beyond their conventional roles in pH sensing and cell imaging [45–50], the yellow-emitting C-dots were applied to detect acidic and alkaline amino acids (Table 1
                        ). Asp and Glu, with isoelectric points of 2.77 and 3.22, respectively, represent acidic amino acids, while Lys, Arg, and His, with isoelectric points of 9.74, 10.76, and 7.59, respectively, represent alkaline amino acids. As illustrated in Fig. 6
                        a, fluorescence intensity changes of the C-dots were measured in the presence of 20 common amino acids. Acidic amino acids quenched fluorescence, while alkaline amino acids enhanced it. Fluorescence titration experiments confirmed these effects (Figs. 6b–f and S6). For Asp (Figs. 6b and S6a) and Glu (Figs. 6c and S6b), the fluorescence intensity decreased gradually with increasing concentrations. Linear relationships were observed between Asp concentration and fluorescence quenching (10.94–29.80 µM, Fig. S7a) with the equation (F0-F)/F0 = 0.0080 [Asp] + 0.0699 (R2 = 0.9989) and a limit of detection (LOD) of 0.242 µM. Similarly, Glu showed a linear response (11.94–47.11 µM, Fig. S7b) with the equation (F0-F)/F0 = 0.0057 [Glu] + 0.0421 (R2 = 0.9970) and an LOD of 0.304 µM. Here, F0 and F represent the fluorescence intensities in the absence and presence of Asp or Glu, respectively, while [Asp] and [Glu] denote their concentrations. In contrast, the addition of Lys, Arg, or His resulted in fluorescence enhancement (Figs. 6d–f and S6c–e). For Lys, the linear range was 7.96–81.54 µM (Fig. S7c) with the equation (F-F0)/F0 = 0.0078 [Lys] + 0.0465 (R2 = 0.9995) and an LOD of 0.290 µM. Arg displayed a linear relationship (6.97–29.80 µM, Fig. S7d) with (F-F0)/F0 = 0.0169 [Arg] + 0.0460 (R2 = 0.9982) and an LOD of 0.138 µM. His showed a linear range of 6.47–28.81 µM (Fig. S7e) with (F-F0)/F0 = 0.0122 [His] + 0.0155 (R2 = 0.9975) and an LOD of 0.081 µM. Here, [Lys], [Arg], and [His] denote their concentrations, while F0 and F represent the fluorescence intensities in the absence and presence of Lys, Arg, or His, respectively. To evaluate the selectivity of the C-dots, their PL intensity was tested before and after adding Asp (Fig. S8a), Glu (Fig. S8b), Lys (Fig. S8c), Arg (Fig. S8d), and His (Fig. S8e) in the presence of other amino acids. The results demonstrate that the C-dots maintained strong resistance to interference, enabling selective detection of acidic and alkaline amino acids even in complex mixtures. These findings highlight the potential of C-dots as a versatile tool for distinguishing amino acids based on their acidic or alkaline properties, paving the way for broader applications in biochemical sensing and analysis.
